  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to prevent the illegal process of concealing the origins of money obtained through criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, corruption, and organized crime. Here are some key international mechanisms:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):**\n   - Established in 1989 by the G7, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF's recommendations are widely recognized as the global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions:**\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This was the first international treaty to address money laundering specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions targeting money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** Known as the Merida Convention, it addresses money laundering in the context of corruption.\n\n3. **European Union Directives:**\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD), which member states are required to transpose into national law. These directives establish a comprehensive framework for AML and CFT within the EU.\n\n4. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank:**\n   - These institutions provide technical assistance and policy advice to member countries to strengthen their AML and CFT frameworks. They also conduct assessments and reviews to ensure compliance with international standards.\n\n5. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision:**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to implement effective AML measures, particularly in the context of Know Your Customer (KYC) and Customer Due Diligence (CDD) procedures.\n\n6. **Interpol and Europol:**\n   - These international law enforcement agencies facilitate cooperation and information sharing among countries to combat money laundering and related crimes.\n\nThese international laws and frameworks are complemented by national legislation in individual countries, which enforce AML practices within their jurisdictions. Compliance with these international standards is crucial for maintaining the integrity of the global financial system and preventing the exploitation of financial institutions for illicit purposes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
